<!-- table:view -->
<table class="view" summary="ABOUT MOHW &gt; Press Release detail.">
<caption>ABOUT MOHW &gt; Press Release</caption>
<colgroup>
<col width="12%"/><col width="38%"/><col width="12%"/><col width="38%"/>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th scope="row">Subject</th>
<td colspan="3">Social Security Agreement between Korea and Spain to come into effect on April 1st</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row">Date</th>
<td>2013-04-04</td>
<th scope="row">Hit</th>
<td>5420</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row">Contents</th>
<td class="view" colspan="3"><p align="center" style="font-size: 14px"><strong>Social Security Agreement   between Korea and Spain to come into effect on April   1st</strong></p>
<p align="center" style="font-size: 14px">- Number of   countries to sign the agreement with Korea to reach 25 - </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">The Ministry of   Foreign Affairs (Minister Yun Byung-se), the Ministry of Health and Welfare   (Minister Chin Young) and the National Pension Service (Chairman and CEO Jun   Kwang-woo) said that the Korea-Spain Social Security Agreement will come into   effect beginning April 1st after approval by each country’ s National   Assembly. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">According to the   agreement between the two countries, </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Workers currently   dispatched to a partner country must pay the social insurance premium to both   countries, but the agreement will exempt these workers from dual payment for a   certain period of time (5 years, extension available). </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">- Thus, Korean   workers dispatched to Spain will be exempted from paying fees for the national   pension and the unemployment insurance in Spain when submitting a subscription   to Korea’ s national pension and the employment insurance to the foreign state,   which will lessen economic burdens of Korean workers as well as companies. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> ¡Ø However, Korean workers sent to Spain   have to subscribe to private health insurance for coverage in Spain, and be   covered by Spain’ s workers’  compensation insurance. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">- For example, a   worker (last name Kim) working at a Korean Company in Spain does not need to pay   Spain’ s annual social insurance premium, worth 19,370,000 won, thanks to the   bilateral Social Security Agreement. </p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="126"><p align="center">Classification </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="163"><p align="center">Before the enforcement of the agreement </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="109"><p align="center">After the enforcement </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="217"><p align="center">Note </p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="126"><p align="center">Spain’ s social insurance premium </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="163"><p align="center">19,370,000 won per year </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="109"><p align="center"><strong>Exemption </strong></p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="217"><p align="center">Social insurance premium rate: : 36.25% of income </p>
<p align="center">(pension 28.3%, unemployment 7.95%)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size: 14px">* Spain’ s   insurance premium-levied upper limit income (36,888 EURO per year) applied   (exchange rate: 1 EURO = 1448.2 won)</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Also, immigrants   who are subscribed to the pension insurance in both Korea and Spain can receive   pensions from both nations as subscription periods are added up. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">- The minimum   coverage period requirement is 10 years in Korea and 15 years in Spain. In   principle, if workers joined the pension system for eight years in Korea and   Spain each, they could not draw their pension from the both nations. However,   the Social Security Agreement acknowledges a total subscription period (in this   case 16 years), and therefore workers can receive a pension from both Korea and   Spain. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> * For receiving a pension from Spain, a   minimum subscription period of 15 years including two years within 15 years   before the age of 65, the starting age for a pension, is required. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> (Case   1)</p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="188"><p align="center">Classification</p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="122"><p align="center">Before the enforcement of the agreement </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="195"><p align="center">After the enforcement </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="119"><p align="center">Note </p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="188"><p align="center">National pension </p>
<p align="center">(subscribed for eight years after the age of 50) </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="122"><p align="center">Not eligible for pension </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="195"><p align="center">Eligible for national pension </p>
<p align="center">(benefits = 8 years/28 years)</p></td>
<td rowspan="2" style="font-size: 14px" width="119"><p align="center"><strong>Subscription period to be acknowledged as 28 years due to the   enforcement of the agreement </strong></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="188"><p align="center">Spain’ s pension</p>
<p align="center">(subscribed for 20 years before the age of 50)</p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="122"><p align="center">Not eligible for pension </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="195"><p align="center">Eligible for Spain’ s pension </p>
<p align="center"> (benefits = 20 years/28   years) </p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size: 14px">(Case   2)</p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tbody>
