<td rowspan="2" style="font-size: 14px" width="119"><p align="center"><strong>Subscription period to be acknowledged as 16 years due to the   enforcement of the agreement</strong></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="188"><p align="center">Spain’ s pension</p>
<p align="center">(subscribed for 20 years before the age of 50) </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="122"><p align="center">Not eligible for pension </p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="199"><p align="center">Eligible for Spain’ s pension (benefits = 8 years/16 years)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size: 14px">As the   Korea-Spain Social Security Agreement comes into effect, Korea will have made   this agreement with a total of 25 countries. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Related   ministries have signed the agreement with the Philippines, Turkey, and Brazil,   and are preparing to begin enforcement. Korea has concurred drafts of the   agreement with Norway, Quebec, Argentina, and Sweden, and is expected to   continuously increase the number of partners for the Social Security Agreement. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Also, Korea plans to diversify the agreement by seeking to sign it   with countries in Latin America, Africa, and Asia in order to expand human   resources and material exchanges with foreign countries and protect the rights   of pensioners working abroad. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Details regarding   the Korea-Spain Social Security Agreement, such as issuing a pension certificate   and a total period of pension subscription, are available at the International   Center of the National Pension Service (call 02-2176-8716). </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">&lt;Attachment   1&gt; Meaning and current signing status of the Social Security   System</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">&lt;Attachment   2&gt; Analysis on the effects of the Korea-Spain Social Security Agreement </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Attachment 1.   Meaning and current signing status of the Social Security   System</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">¢Â What is the   Social Security Agreement? </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">: The Social   Security Agreement is a bilateral agreement to solve disadvantages regarding   social security systems, including limitations in the pension system that   foreigners or Korean nationals abroad can face, and is treated equally with   local laws.</p>
<ol style="font-size: 14px">
<li>- (Totalization of Coverage Periods) People who meet the minimum   coverage period requirements by adding the years they worked in their home   country and the years they worked in the contracting country are eligible for   pension benefits from both countries for their respective years of service. </li>
<li>- (Elimination of Dual Coverage)   Workers abroad are exempted from joining the pension program in contracting   countries if they join the pension service in their   homeland.</li>
</ol>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> &lt; Countries where the Social Security   Agreement comes into effect (a total of 25 countries) &gt; </p>
<table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="159"><p align="center"><strong>Effects</strong></p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="446"><p align="center"><strong>Name of country </strong></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="159"><p align="center">Elimination of Dual Coverage </p>
<p align="center">(8 countries)</p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="446"><p>Iran ((Jun ’ 78) U.K.(Aug ‘ 00), Netherlands(Oct ‘ 03), Japan(April ‘ 05., Italy(April ’ 05), Uzbekistan(May ’ 06), Mongolia(March ’ 07), China(Jan ’ 13)* </p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="159"><p align="center">Elimination of Dual Coverage </p>
<p align="center">+</p>
<p align="center">Totalization of Coverage Periods </p>
<p align="center">(17 countries)</p></td>
<td style="font-size: 14px" width="446"><p>Canada(May ’ 99), U.S.(April ’ 01), Germany(Jan ’ 03), Hungary(March ’ 07), France(June ’ 07), Australia(Oct ’ 08), Czech(Nov ’ 08), Ireland(Jan ’ 09), Belgium(July ’ 09), Poland(April ’ 10), Bulgaria(April ’ 10), Slovakia(April ’ 10), Rumania(’ July 10), Austria(Oct ’ 10), Denmark(Sept ’ 11), India(Nov ’ 11), Spain(April ’ 13)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size: 14px">* Korea signed   tentative measures with China in February, 2003 to define the Elimination of   Dual Coverage, but the bilateral Social Security Agreement came into effect   (January 16th, 2013) with an expanded range of applied insurance and   subjects.</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Attachment 2.   Analysis on the effects of the Korea-Spain Social Security Agreement </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">Analyzing a   financial profit gained by the Elimination of Dual Coverage in the Korea-Spain   Social Security Agreement, the Korean side (Korean companies and people) is   estimated to gain 432,000,000 won per year. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">About 49 Korean   workers are dispatched to Spain, and pay around 949,000,000 won per year for   insurance premiums in Spain. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> * A total of 4,080 Koreans live in Spain. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">About 75 Spanish   workers are dispatched to Korea, and pay 517,000,000 won for insurance premiums   per year in Korea. </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px">* A total of 552   Spanish people live in Korea. </p>
<p align="center" style="font-size: 14px">Exemption amounts   for insurance premiums from the bilateral agreement   (estimation)</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> Reduced fiscal   burdens of Korean workers dispatched to Spain: around 949,000,000 won annually </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> 949,000,000 won = 49 workers × 3,074Euro ×   36.25%× 12 months× 1,448.2 won </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 49 workers: Korean workers dispatched   to Spain (KOTRA, directory of Korean companies advancing into foreign markets in   2011/2012)</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 3,074 Euros: upper limits of monthly   incomes to levy social insurance premiums in Spain </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 36.25%: social insurance premium in   Spain (pension 28.3%, unemployment   7.95%)</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 1,448.2 won: exchange rate as of   March, 2013 </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> Reduced fiscal   burdens of Spanish workers dispatched to Korea: around 517,000,000 won annually </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> 517,000,000 won = 75 workers × 3,123,000 won ×   18.39% × 12 months </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 75 workers: number of Spanish workers   dispatched to Korea (national pension   subscribers)</p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 3,123,000 won: average income of   Spanish workers who subscribe to Korea’ s national pension </p>
<p style="font-size: 14px"> - 18.39%: social insurance premium rate   in Korea (pension 9%, health 6.27%, workers’  compensation 1.77%, employment   1.35%) </p></td>
</tr>
